properties.Name: DunBradstreetKeyBusinessRatios
properties.Description:
Measures the relationship between financial values in a company's balance sheet and income statement. The ratios offer a way to evaluate the performance and stability of a business when you're looking to set credit limits and lending terms for new and existing accounts, assess key suppliers, perform competitive analysis, or research the financial standing of a potential business partner or acquisition candidate.

Industry Norms for these ratios provide a side-by-side comparison of a business with it's industry peers. These norms can help you spot important trends, identify strengths and weaknesses, or serve as a benchmark for evaluating company risk. Industry Norms are based on the SIC code of the company you are inquiring on, as well as the firm's geographic location and total asset size, when available. They represent median statistics derived from D&B's financial statement database of public and private companies, which is updated on a quarterly basis.

Columns.Name: DunsNumber
Columns.Description: Dun & Bradstreet (D&B) provides a D-U-N-S Number, a unique nine digit identification number, for each physical location of your business.

Columns.Name: ReportPurchaseDate
Columns.Description: The purchase date of the report.

Columns.Name: ReturnOnSalesRatioThisBusiness
Columns.Description:
The Return On Sales ratio for the business.

Return on sales (aka operating profit margin) is a financial ratio that calculates how efficiently a company to generate profits from its revenue.

This ratio measures a company's performance by analyzing what percentage of total company revenues are actually converted into company profits.

Columns.Name: ReturnOnSalesRatioIndustryMedian
Columns.Description:
The Return On Sales ratio median value for the industry.

Return on sales (aka operating profit margin) is a financial ratio that calculates how efficiently a company to generate profits from its revenue.

This ratio measures a company's performance by analyzing what percentage of total company revenues are actually converted into company profits.

Columns.Name: ReturnOnSalesRatioIndustryQuartile
Columns.Description: The associated industry quartile ranking associated with the ratio.

Columns.Name: ReturnOnNetWorthRatioThisBusiness
Columns.Description:
The Net Worth Ratio for the company.

This is aka 'Return On Equity'. This ratio tells how much the business is making from invested funds.   It is an overall indicator of operating efficiency and quality of management.10% is considered a good target.

Columns.Name: ReturnOnNetWorthRatioIndustryMedian
Columns.Description:
The Net Worth Ratio for the industry.

This is aka 'Return On Equity'. This ratio tells how much the business is making from invested funds.   It is an overall indicator of operating efficiency and quality of management.10% is considered a good target.

Columns.Name: ReturnOnNetWorthRatioIndustryQuartile
Columns.Description: The associated industry quartile ranking associated with the ratio.

Columns.Name: CurrentRatioThisBusiness
Columns.Description:
The current ratio for the business.

The current ratio is a liquidity ratio that measures a company's ability to pay short-term and long-term obligations. T

The current ratio considers the current total assets of a company (both liquid and illiquid) relative to that company's current total liabilities.

Columns.Name: CurrentRatioIndustryMedian
Columns.Description:
The median current ratio for the industry.

The current ratio is a liquidity ratio that measures a company's ability to pay short-term and long-term obligations. T

The current ratio considers the current total assets of a company (both liquid and illiquid) relative to that company's current total liabilities.

Columns.Name: CurrentRatioIndustryQuartile
Columns.Description: The associated industry quartile ranking associated with the ratio.

Columns.Name: QuickRatioThisBusiness
Columns.Description:
The quick ratio for the business.

The quick ratio is a measure of how well a company can meet its short-term financial liabilities.

The ratio can be calculated as follows: (Cash + Marketable Securities + Accounts Receivable) / Current Liabilities.

Columns.Name: QuickRatioIndustryMedian
Columns.Description:
The industry quick ratio.

The quick ratio for the business.

The quick ratio is a measure of how well a company can meet its short-term financial liabilities.

The ratio can be calculated as follows: (Cash + Marketable Securities + Accounts Receivable) / Current Liabilities.

Columns.Name: QuickRatioIndustryQuartile
Columns.Description: The associated industry quartile ranking associated with the ratio.

Columns.Name: AssetSalesRatioThisBusiness
Columns.Description:
The asset sales ratio for the business.

Asset turnover ratio is the ratio of the value of a company's sales or revenues generated relative to the value of its assets. 

The Asset Turnover ratio can often be used as an indicator of the efficiency with which a company is deploying its assets in generating revenue.

Columns.Name: AssetSalesRatioIndustryMedian
Columns.Description:
The median asset sales ratio for the industry.

Asset turnover ratio is the ratio of the value of a company's sales or revenues generated relative to the value of its assets. 

The Asset Turnover ratio can often be used as an indicator of the efficiency with which a company is deploying its assets in generating revenue.

Columns.Name: AssetSalesRatioIndustryQuartile
Columns.Description: The associated industry quartile ranking associated with the ratio.

Columns.Name: SalesNetWorkingCapitalRatioThisBusiness
Columns.Description:
The sales/net working capital ratio for the business.

The working capital turnover ratio is also referred to as net sales to working capital. It indicates a company's effectiveness in using its working capital. 

The working capital turnover ratio is calculated as follows: net annual sales divided by the average amount of working capital during the same 12 month period.

Columns.Name: SalesNetWorkingCapitalRatioIndustryMedian
Columns.Description:
The median sales/net working capital ratio for the industry.

The working capital turnover ratio is also referred to as net sales to working capital. It indicates a company's effectiveness in using its working capital. 

The working capital turnover ratio is calculated as follows: net annual sales divided by the average amount of working capital during the same 12 month period.

Columns.Name: SalesNetWorkingCapitalRatioIndustryQuartile
Columns.Description: The associated industry quartile ranking associated with the ratio.

Columns.Name: TotalLiabilitiesNetWorthRatioThisBusiness
Columns.Description:
The total liabilities/net worth ratio for the business (aka debt/equity ratio).

Debt/Equity Ratio is a debt ratio used to measure a company's financial leverage, calculated by dividing a company's total liabilities by its stockholders' equity. 

The D/E ratio indicates how much debt a company is using to finance its assets relative to the amount of value represented in shareholders' equity.

Columns.Name: TotalLiabilitiesNetWorthRatioIndustryMedian
Columns.Description:
The median industry total liabilities/net worth ratio.

Debt/Equity Ratio is a debt ratio used to measure a company's financial leverage, calculated by dividing a company's total liabilities by its stockholders' equity. 

The D/E ratio indicates how much debt a company is using to finance its assets relative to the amount of value represented in shareholders' equity.

Columns.Name: TotalLiabilitiesNetWorthRatioIndustryQuartile
Columns.Description: The associated industry quartile ranking associated with the ratio.
